For those whose knowledge of BMC (Bovine malignant catarrh) is rusty, James
kindly provided this additional information. MHJ]
Sorry. In this part of the world one gets used to terms etc that are
considered everyday for south (sub-Saharan) Africa.
Bovine Malinant Catarrhal fever (BMC)
Also refered to as Malignant Catarrhal Fever (MCF), mainly in the nothern
hemisphere. Strictly speaking they are different.
Now you probably know what I refer to. A good and recent overview will be
found in:
Infectious diseases of livestock. Coetzer JAW, Thomson GR and
Tustin RC. Oxford University Press, 1994. (page 946)

MCF is a viral disease of cattle and deer with a worldwide distribution. It
is sheep associated and has been recognised first in the late 1800. In South
Africa we only see the disease very occasionally.
BMC is a wildebeest (primarily blue wildebeest) associated caused by a
herpes virus that is isolated with difficulty. In eastern Africa the disease
is of particular importance where in some areas and some years it is
estimated that the disease causes up to 20% mortality in cattle. The disease
is invariably fatal but morbidity is usually low.
Antigens can be detected by PCR and can be differentiated by this method.
............................................................mhj

